---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Section from '../../components/Section.astro';
import Button from '../../components/Button.astro';

const publishedDate = '2026-05-24';
const author = 'Jason Bauman';
const authorTitle = 'Cofounder, WKTW';
const readingTime = '6 min read';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Why Most Audits Don't Change Anything"
  description="There's a structural reason your last six-figure audit ended up in a Google Drive folder nobody opens. It's not your team — it's the shape of the work."
>
  <Section class="pt-28 pb-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-4">
        <a href="/insights" class="hover:text-accent-hover">Insights</a> &rsaquo; Audit Process
      </p>
      <h1 class="mb-6">Why most audits don't change anything.</h1>
      <p class="text-secondary-text text-xl leading-relaxed mb-8">
        There's a structural reason your last six-figure audit ended up in
        a Google Drive folder nobody opens. It's not your team. It's the
        shape of the work.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-4 text-secondary-text text-sm border-t border-border-subtle pt-6">
        <span class="text-primary-text font-medium">{author}</span>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <span>{authorTitle}</span>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <time datetime={publishedDate}>May 24, 2026</time>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <span>{readingTime}</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section>
    <article class="max-w-3xl prose-invert">
      <div class="space-y-6 text-secondary-text text-lg leading-relaxed">

        <p>
          Here's the pattern I've watched play out at three agencies over twelve
          years. A company decides their site is underperforming. They have a
          gut feeling, or a board slide, or a quarter where conversions dipped
          and nobody could explain it. So they hire someone to audit it.
        </p>

        <p>
          Six weeks later, a PDF arrives. It's two hundred pages. It has
          color-coded severity ratings and a beautifully formatted executive
          summary. It mentions Core Web Vitals. It uses the word
          &ldquo;opportunities&rdquo; a lot.
        </p>

        <p>
          Their dev team opens it once. They can't figure out what to do first.
          They file it in the shared drive. Nothing ships. Three quarters later,
          someone in a planning meeting goes &ldquo;wait, didn't we do an audit
          last year? What happened with that?&rdquo; And the answer is: nothing
          happened with that. That's the default outcome for most audits in
          this industry, and the reason isn't laziness on anyone's part. It's
          the shape of the deliverable.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-primary-text text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          The three failure modes
        </h2>

        <p>
          Audits fail to produce change for three structural reasons. They're
          almost always happening together, which is why teams that try to fix
          one of them in isolation still end up with a binder nobody opens.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-primary-text text-xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-3">
          1. Symptoms instead of root causes.
        </h3>

        <p>
          Most audits list two hundred findings. The number itself is the tell.
          A real site doesn't have two hundred independent problems. It has
          maybe thirty root causes producing two hundred downstream symptoms.
          Your render-blocking JavaScript, your unminified CSS, your missing
          cache headers, and your slow LCP are often the same problem wearing
          four costumes &mdash; the build pipeline isn't tree-shaking your
          vendor bundle correctly, and every page inherits the cost.
        </p>

        <p>
          When the audit lists the symptoms instead of the cluster, your
          engineering team has to do the root-cause analysis themselves &mdash;
          which is exactly the work they were paying you to do. So they don't.
          And the audit dies.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-primary-text text-xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-3">
          2. Advisory instead of implementation-ready.
        </h3>

        <p>
          &ldquo;Consider optimizing your images&rdquo; is not an instruction.
          It's a writing prompt for the person who actually has to do the work.
          The same goes for &ldquo;implement structured data,&rdquo; &ldquo;improve
          your internal linking,&rdquo; and the perennial favorite, &ldquo;ensure
          your site is mobile-friendly.&rdquo;
        </p>

        <p>
          An audit finding that doesn't include the config change, the file
          path, the specific snippet, and the order to apply it in isn't a
          finding. It's homework. It transfers the diagnostic work from the
          auditor (who was supposed to have done it) to the engineer (who now
          has to redo it from scratch before they can ship anything). Most
          engineers, very reasonably, look at the homework and find something
          else to work on.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-primary-text text-xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-3">
          3. Best-practice anchored instead of revenue-anchored.
        </h3>

        <p>
          &ldquo;This is a best practice&rdquo; is the four most useless words
          in this industry. Best practice for whom? Costing you what? Compared
          to which alternative? A finding that doesn't connect to a dollar
          number doesn't survive contact with a quarterly planning meeting.
          The conversation in that meeting is always about revenue, never about
          best practices &mdash; and a finding that can't enter that conversation
          gets cut.
        </p>

        <p>
          Every real finding in a real audit needs to answer one question:
          <strong class="text-primary-text">if we fix this, what does it
          recover, in dollars, per month, conservatively.</strong> If you can't
          answer that, you don't actually know whether the fix is worth doing.
          And if you don't know whether it's worth doing, your client can't
          prioritize it against the other forty things on their roadmap.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-primary-text text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          The synthesis problem
        </h2>

        <p>
          Even when an audit gets the three things above right, there's a fourth
          failure mode that quietly kills most engagements. Modern digital
          properties have three independent failure surfaces: the infrastructure
          (server, platform, frontend), the content (what questions you answer
          and how authoritatively), and the measurement (whether your analytics
          is telling the truth at all). They all leak revenue. They all interact.
          And almost no audit looks at more than one of them.
        </p>

        <p>
          What ends up happening is the technical agency says &ldquo;your LCP
          is bad,&rdquo; the content agency says &ldquo;you need more
          topic-cluster pages,&rdquo; and the analytics consultant says
          &ldquo;your GA4 is undercounting by 14%.&rdquo; All three are right.
          None of them know about the others. The client gets three roadmaps
          and now has to decide which one to actually execute &mdash; which
          becomes a political question instead of a strategic one, because
          nobody synthesized the findings into one ranked plan.
        </p>

        <p>
          The synthesis is the thing. A unified roadmap that says &ldquo;fix
          this server config first because it unblocks these four content
          improvements, which won't show up in analytics until you fix this
          tracking gap, and the total revenue impact across the chain is $X
          per month over six months&rdquo; is the deliverable that actually
          ships. Three separate reports is the deliverable that sits in a
          drive.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-primary-text text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          What to demand instead
        </h2>

        <p>
          If you're commissioning an audit &mdash; any audit, from anyone &mdash;
          here's the four-line spec to hand them before you sign:
        </p>

        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3">
          <li>
            Every finding has a <strong class="text-primary-text">root cause</strong>,
            not a symptom. If you list two hundred items, I'm going to ask you
            which thirty of them are the actual underlying problems.
          </li>
          <li>
            Every finding is <strong class="text-primary-text">implementation-ready</strong>.
            Config snippets, file paths, the specific change. If my engineer
            has to do the diagnostic work to ship the fix, you haven't audited
            anything &mdash; you've written a reading list.
          </li>
          <li>
            Every finding is <strong class="text-primary-text">revenue-anchored</strong>.
            Conservative dollar estimate, monthly. Show your math. I'll accept
            ranges; I won't accept &ldquo;this is a best practice.&rdquo;
          </li>
          <li>
            The output is <strong class="text-primary-text">one ranked plan</strong>,
            not three separate documents. If you can't synthesize across
            infrastructure, content, and measurement, you're missing two of the
            three places revenue actually leaks.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          That's the audit shape that ships. It's also the audit shape this
          industry mostly refuses to deliver, because it's significantly harder
          to produce than a two-hundred-page PDF. The agencies and tools that
          do produce it are rare, and worth what they charge. Everything else
          is content for a Google Drive folder.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-primary-text text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          Why we care about this
        </h2>

        <p>
          We built WKTW because we kept watching audits like the ones above get
          commissioned and then quietly die. Every cofounder at this company
          has shipped audits the other way at some point in their career &mdash;
          the two-hundred-page kind, the &ldquo;consider optimizing&rdquo; kind,
          the one-of-three-disconnected-roadmaps kind. We're not above the
          critique. We've contributed to the pile.
        </p>

        <p>
          The Get Right is what happens when you build the diagnostic tools
          yourself, run all three audit lenses in parallel, and refuse to ship
          anything that doesn't pass the four-line spec above. Root cause,
          implementation-ready, revenue-anchored, one ranked plan. If a finding
          can't meet those four bars, it doesn't go in the deliverable.
        </p>

        <p>
          That's the whole product. Everything else is marketing.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border-subtle">
        <h3 class="text-primary-text text-xl mb-4">Want to see what we'd find?</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary-text mb-6">
          Free scan, no commitment. We'll run our structural audit on your site
          and surface 5&ndash;10 of the highest-severity findings, each with the
          root cause and confidence tier. If they're useful, the full Get Right
          finds 30&ndash;40 more.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4">
          <Button href="/scan">Run a Free Scan</Button>
          <Button href="/the-get-right" variant="secondary">Learn about The Get Right</Button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </Section>
</BaseLayout>
